<subSubSection type="etymology">
<paragraph pageNumber="688">
Etymology L 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33734" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole fabricator (Smith)" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole fabricator (Smith)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="688" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fabricator">fabricator</taxonomicName>
, maker, builder.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageNumber="688">
Diagnosis A member of the 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:34070" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole tristis (Smith)" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole tristis (Smith)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="688" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tristis">tristis</taxonomicName>
group similar to 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33606" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole balzani Emery" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole balzani Emery" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="688" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="balzani">balzani</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:182060" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole nigella Emery" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole nigella Emery" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="688" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigella">nigella</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:34070" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole tristis (Smith)" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole tristis (Smith)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="688" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tristis">tristis</taxonomicName>
, and distinguished from these and other species in the group by the following traits.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="description">
<paragraph pageNumber="688">Major: hypostoma 2-toothed; Head Width greater than Head Length; head with mandibles tapering anteriorly, and overall heartshaped; entire anterior dorsal half of head longitudinally carinulate, including frontal triangle and middle section of clypeus. measurements (mm) Syntype major: HW 1.18, HL 1.12, SL 0.60, EL 0.14, PW 0.54. Minor (Caraguatatuba, Brazil): HW 0.52, HL 0.56, SL 0.52, EL 0.12, PW 0.32.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="688">Color Major: body reddish brown except for gaster, which is plain dark brown; appendages medium to dark brown.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="688">Minor: head plain medium brown except for the genae, which are yellowish brown; mesosoma brownish yellow; gaster dark brown;</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="688">appendages light brown.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="distribution">
<paragraph pageNumber="688">
Range In addition to the syntype from Rio de Janeiro, and series cited in the figure caption from Sao Paulo, I have seen a series of 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33734" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole fabricator (Smith)" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole fabricator (Smith)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="688" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fabricator">fabricator</taxonomicName>
from Rancho Grande, Aragua, Venezuela, 1100 m (W. L. and D. E. Brown). Kempf (1972b) reports the species in addition from the state of Santa Catarina in Brazil. I have also examined the same or possibly a closely related species from near Belem, Para, Brazil; and from the Guayabero River, Meta, Colombia.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph pageNumber="688">Biology An inhabitant of rainforest. Males were present in a nest at Rancho Grande, Venezuela, during the time of collection, 23-27 June.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
